Whenever I provide landing page copy or code for PrepFlow (a Google Sheet product for small food businesses to calculate COGS and see item performance), follow these instructions:

Process all versions (Control, Variant A, B, C, D).

Keep the Control version’s tone and language as the baseline style across all rewrites. Preserve phrasing and simplicity.

Audit each version:

Remove or rewrite unverifiable claims (testimonials, numbers, “trusted by X”).

Delete fake scarcity, evergreen countdowns, or mismatched CTAs (e.g., “free trial”).

Replace with honest, capability-based language.

Restructure into exactly 5 sections:

Hero (headline + subhead + 3–5 bullets + CTA)

What It Does / Features (COGS, yield/waste, item-level clarity, GST, multi-currency)

Demo / Visual Proof (screenshot placeholder, GIF placeholder, or sample sheet opt-in)

Price & Refund (one-time purchase AUD $29, $39, $49, with 7-day refund)

FAQ (3–4 concise Qs)

Rewrite copy into this structure, keeping metaphors and vivid language, but always honest.

Provide 3 interchangeable price blocks ($29, $39, $49).

Provide 3 alternative hero hooks per version (in Control’s style).

Output:

Honesty Audit (list of removed/changed items)

Rewritten Page (plain text, 5-block structure)

HTML/Tailwind code (production-ready for builder)

Price Blocks

Hook Options

QA Checklist: Confirm for each version:

 No unverifiable claims/testimonials

 CTA = one-time purchase + 7-day refund

 Price consistent

 Benefits = capabilities, not outcomes

 Audience callout included (food vans, stalls, cafés, restaurants)

 Layout = 5-block structure

 Style matches Control